    {
        "user": "UCUSW7WVD",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1704912755.592039",
        "client_msg_id": "f6717139-ed93-4f8d-96ec-836b08701c69",
        "text": "I don't have data but anecdotally the Linux kernel definitely has a well-known problem recruiting new maintainers. The existing ones are overworked, nobody knows what will happen when they burn out, retire, etc.\n\ne.g. <https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209|https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209>\n\nIt makes sense to me. Historically specialization has formal funnels leading into it, and there's some amount of price elasticity in the face of constrained supply. Low level open source projects add impedance on both sides of that. Historically the open source funnel starts with using something and starting to hack on it. But today we have so many layers we are not even aware of using. Meanwhile the major projects continue to grow compoundingly complex over time (so you need more recruiting this year than you did last year). Private enterprise growth rates feel like a bad fit for open source, but the combination is all too common.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "6e649a383cf8",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2019-07-14\/687915485201_6e649a383cf8f9e366e3_72.png",
            "first_name": "Kartik",
            "real_name": "Kartik Agaram",
            "display_name": "",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "ak",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1703941495.921419",
        "parent_user_id": "U5STGTB3J",
        "attachments": [
            {
                "from_url": "https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209",
                "service_icon": "https:\/\/static.lwn.net\/images\/favicon.png",
                "id": 1,
                "original_url": "https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209",
                "fallback": "Reducing kernel-maintainer burnout",
                "text": "Overstressed maintainers are a constant topic of conversation throughout\nthe open-source community. Kernel maintainers have been complaining more\nloudly than usual recently about overwork and stress. The problems that\nmaintainers are facing are clear; what to do about them is rather less so.\nA session at the 2023 Maintainers Summit took up the topic yet again with\nthe hope of finding some solutions; there may be answers, perhaps even\nwithin the kernel community, but a general solution still seems distant.",
                "title": "Reducing kernel-maintainer burnout",
                "title_link": "https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209",
                "service_name": "lwn.net"
            }
        ],
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "GVByS",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "I don't have data but anecdotally the Linux kernel definitely has a well-known problem recruiting new maintainers. The existing ones are overworked, nobody knows what will happen when they burn out, retire, etc.\n\ne.g. "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209",
                                "text": "https:\/\/lwn.net\/SubscriberLink\/952034\/922c90d8097bd209"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nIt makes sense to me. Historically specialization has formal funnels leading into it, and there's some amount of price elasticity in the face of constrained supply. Low level open source projects add impedance on both sides of that. Historically the open source funnel starts with using something and starting to hack on it. But today we have so many layers we are not even aware of using. Meanwhile the major projects continue to grow compoundingly complex over time (so you need more recruiting this year than you did last year). Private enterprise growth rates feel like a bad fit for open source, but the combination is all too common."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
